---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Chapter from "../components/Chapter.astro";
import Lesson from "../components/Lesson.astro";
import Artifact from "../components/Artifact.astro";
---

<Base title="Navigating the Idea Maze | Tools for Sovereignty">
  <!-- Hero -->
  <header class="container hero">
    <p class="hero-overline">Year One / April 2025 - April 2026</p>
    <h1 class="hero-title">
      Navigating the<br />Idea Maze
    </h1>
    <div class="hero-intro">
      <p>
        We've spent the last year navigating the
        <a class="inline-link" href="https://cdixon.org/2013/08/04/the-idea-maze" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">idea maze</a>.
        We built things that worked and things that didn't.
        We learned a lot.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is an account of what we worked on, why we found it interesting,
        and what we learned from it.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="hero-readings">
      <p class="hero-readings-label">Frameworks</p>
      <ul class="hero-readings-list">
        <li>
          <a href="https://cdixon.org/2013/08/04/the-idea-maze" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">The Idea Maze</a>
          <span class="reading-attr"> / Chris Dixon</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://www.lennysnewsletter.com/p/finding-product-market-fit" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Finding Product-Market Fit</a>
          <span class="reading-attr"> / Lenny Rachitsky</span>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://posthog.com/founders/product-market-fit-game" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">The Product-Market Fit Game</a>
          <span class="reading-attr"> / PostHog</span>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </header>

  <!-- The Maze -->
  <div class="container maze" id="maze">

    <!-- PRE-INCORPORATION -->
    <div style="margin-bottom: 4rem;">
      <p class="maze-era">Before incorporation</p>
    </div>

    <Chapter date="October 2024" title="The Startup Company" status="dead-end">
      <p>
        Let anyone incorporate a company on the internet, on-chain.
        We called it TSC, The Startup Company. We found Sark, a tiny crown
        dependency near Jersey and Guernsey that didn't have company law,
        and explored writing company law with them. We looked at Argentina.
        We looked at EU Inc. We imagined a batchless Y Combinator, a neobank
        built on zero-knowledge proofs.
      </p>
      <Lesson type="insight">
        On-chain company formation was a genuinely unsolved problem. The
        regulatory surface area was fascinating, and ZK-proofs for financial
        identity felt like the future.
      </Lesson>
      <Lesson type="pivot">
        Jurisdictional innovation moves at government speed. We were building
        software on a regulatory timeline.
      </Lesson>
    </Chapter>

    <Chapter date="November 2024" title="What Did You Get Done This Week?" status="dead-end">
      <p>
        A Slack bot that asked your team one question every week: "What did
        you get done?" Simple accountability, async standups, a lightweight
        way to keep distributed teams in sync.
      </p>
      <Lesson type="insight">
        Teams wanted visibility into what everyone was working on, but they
        didn't want another tool to manage. The friction was the format, not
        the intent.
      </Lesson>
      <Lesson type="pivot">
        A Slack bot is a feature, not a company. But it planted a seed: the
        interesting problem was what happens to all that context after you
        collect it.
      </Lesson>
    </Chapter>

    <Chapter date="November - December 2024" title="Selling Your Own Data" status="dead-end">
      <p>
        What if people could sell their personal data to model companies? A
        marketplace for user data, powered by crypto. The user owns it, the
        user sells it, the buyer gets training data they can trust.
      </p>
      <Lesson type="insight">
        The idea of user-owned data was compelling. Crypto economics offered
        a credible mechanism for provenance and payment. The demand side
        (model companies needing diverse, high-quality training data) felt real.
      </Lesson>
      <Lesson type="pivot">
        The economics didn't work. Individual data isn't valuable enough to
        create a functioning marketplace, and the infrastructure needed to
        make it trustworthy was enormous.
      </Lesson>
    </Chapter>

    <Chapter date="January - April 2025" title="The Worldcoin Bet">
      <p>
        We went all in on building AI mini-apps inside the World (formerly
        Worldcoin) ecosystem. First came Sage, an AI assistant that became the
        biggest AI app on World, reaching 250,000 users. Then Bestie, a
        companion app.
      </p>
      <p>
        We had distribution. We had users. We were learning what people
        actually wanted from AI that knew them.
      </p>
      <Lesson type="insight">
        Distribution without ownership is renting. We had 250K users on
        someone else's platform. But we learned something critical: people
        want AI that remembers them.
      </Lesson>
      <div style="margin-top: 1rem;">
        <Artifact label="Sage" type="link" />
        <Artifact label="Bestie" type="link" />
      </div>
    </Chapter>

    <!-- INCORPORATION -->
    <div class="incorporation">
      <div class="incorporation-inner">
        <p class="incorporation-label">April 2025 / Incorporation</p>
        <p class="incorporation-text">
          Tools for Sovereignty becomes a company. The name is a riff on Tools for Humanity.
        </p>
        <div style="margin-top: 0.75rem;">
          <Artifact
            label="The name"
            type="tweet"
            href="https://x.com/arthaud_/status/1981768176049246422"
          />
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- POST-INCORPORATION -->
    <div style="margin-bottom: 4rem;">
      <p class="maze-era">After incorporation</p>
    </div>

    <Chapter date="May - September 2025" title="Sovereign Memory" status="dead-end">
      <p>
        The insight from Worldcoin was clear: AI needs to know who you are.
        So we built private user memory. RAG pipelines with client-side
        embeddings. Trusted execution environments like Phala. Your data
        stays with you, AI just reads it.
      </p>
      <p>
        The tech was elegant. Personalization from the very first interaction,
        without anyone ever seeing your data. We wrote a manifesto about why
        this mattered: reclaiming the web, building the missing context layer
        for AI, making portability the default.
      </p>
      <Lesson type="insight">
        Privacy-preserving personalization was technically beautiful. Client-side
        embeddings, TEEs, and user-controlled data felt like the right
        architecture for a post-platform internet.
      </Lesson>
      <Lesson type="pivot">
        Apps don't care about privacy. We were solving a user problem that
        buyers (the apps integrating us) didn't value. Pragmatism over ideology.
      </Lesson>
      <div style="margin-top: 1rem;">
        <Artifact label="The Manifesto" type="link" href="/manifesto" />
      </div>
    </Chapter>

    <Chapter date="September - December 2025" title="The Identity Play" status="dead-end">
      <p>
        If privacy wasn't the hook, maybe convenience was. We built an IAM
        provider: log in once, connect your data once, and every app just
        works. No re-sharing, no re-onboarding, no repeating yourself.
        Portable identity for the AI era.
      </p>
      <Lesson type="insight">
        The onboarding problem was real. Every new AI app asks you the same
        questions, connects the same accounts, starts from zero. A shared
        identity layer that carried context across apps was a clean abstraction.
      </Lesson>
      <Lesson type="pivot">
        Identity is a feature, not a product. Nobody wakes up wanting a
        better login. They want better tools.
      </Lesson>
    </Chapter>

    <Chapter date="January - February 2026" title="Fast Iterations">
      <p>
        Memory infrastructure was a bad market. Customers folded through.
        We started moving fast, testing ideas in weeks instead of months.
        Action produces information.
      </p>
      <p>
        Context seeding. MCP aggregator. Portable company context across LLMs.
        Each iteration got closer to something real. Then we discovered
        Open Claw and the world of self-hosted agents, and something clicked.
      </p>
      <Lesson type="insight">
        Speed itself was the strategy. Each dead idea produced the information
        we needed for the next one. Don't overthink. Ship, learn, kill, repeat.
      </Lesson>
    </Chapter>

    <Chapter date="March - April 2026" title="Context Drift" status="active-path">
      <p>
        We started asking a different question: what actually breaks when you
        adopt agentic engineering? The answer is context. Agents drift.
        Knowledge fragments. Teams lose coherence.
      </p>
      <p>
        We built a reconciliation tool. Then we realized reconciliation is
        just the beginning. The real opportunity is automating work itself.
        That's where we are today. An agent that lives in Slack, automating
        the work that knowledge workers do every day.
      </p>
      <Lesson type="insight">
        The idea maze doesn't end. You just get better at reading the walls.
      </Lesson>
    </Chapter>

    <!-- Maze end -->
    <div class="maze-end">
      <div class="maze-end-inner">
        <p class="maze-end-text">
          One year in. Still searching.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</Base>
